<div class="badge"><span class="badge-dot"></span>FRACTIONAL CMO · PROFESSIONAL SERVICES</div>
<h1 class="hero-h">Fractional CMO for <em style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif;font-style:italic;color:#00C853;">professional services firms.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Law, accounting, consulting, A/E practices. Different business model from product companies — relationship-led, partner-driven, slow-cycle, reputation-sensitive. The fractional CMO model fits well, but only if the leader understands how marketing actually drives new client work at firms where the partners are the product.</p>
</div></div>


<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Why the model fits</span>
<h2 class="h2">What makes professional services different</h2>
<p class="body">Professional services firms don't sell products; they sell trust, relationships, and the partners' judgment. Marketing at these firms is not lead-gen in the typical SaaS sense — it's brand-and-reputation work that creates the conditions for partners to win new client engagements through their relationships and referral networks.</p>
<p class="body">A fractional CMO who lands at a professional services firm and tries to run a B2B SaaS playbook (paid acquisition, MQL targets, lead scoring) will burn time and credibility quickly. The right playbook is different.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The right playbook</span>
<h2 class="h2">What actually moves new client work</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Partner-led thought leadership at scale.</strong> Partners write, speak, and publish. The fractional CMO builds the infrastructure (AI-assisted drafting, distribution, repurposing) so partners produce 3-4x more content with the same time investment.</li>
<li><strong>Referral-friendly digital presence.</strong> Most professional services clients are referred. The website's job is to convert a referred prospect from "I heard about you" to "I want to meet" — which is a different conversion job than acquiring cold leads.</li>
<li><strong>Industry conference and association presence.</strong> Where partners build the relationships that close work. Marketing's job is making partner conference time more productive — better pre-event outreach, better follow-up, better content amplification.</li>
<li><strong>Practice-area positioning sharpening.</strong> Most firms have weak practice-area differentiation. A fractional CMO who can clarify "we do X better than alternatives because Y" creates measurable lift in partner business-development conversations.</li>
<li><strong>Client experience as marketing.</strong> Existing clients are the firm's biggest source of new work (cross-sell + referral). Marketing the client experience itself is high-leverage.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Engagement structure</span>
<h2 class="h2">What partners ask for</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Reports to managing partner</strong> or marketing committee, often via the executive director / COO.</li>
<li><strong>Engagement length:</strong> Typically 12-24 months — partner adoption takes time and breaks if the engagement ends prematurely.</li>
<li><strong>Honest about partner control.</strong> Partners own client relationships; marketing serves them. A fractional CMO who tries to centralize control will be politely ignored.</li>
<li><strong>Compensation structure aligned to firm norms.</strong> Monthly retainer; rarely equity (partnership structures don't accommodate it well).</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">When fractional fits, when it doesn't</span>
<h2 class="h2">Fit by firm size and stage</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Firm size</th><th>Fit for fractional CMO</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>Solo / 2-3 partners</td><td>Usually no — owner-managed marketing or part-time contractor</td></tr>
<tr><td>4-15 partners, no marketing leader</td><td><strong>Strong fit</strong></td></tr>
<tr><td>15-50 partners, mid-stage</td><td><strong>Strong fit</strong>, often dual-role with marketing director</td></tr>
<tr><td>50+ partners</td><td>Usually needs full-time CMO; fractional can bridge during search</td></tr>
<tr><td>Mid-merger or rebrand phase</td><td>Strong fit — fractional CMO leads the transition</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The AI angle</span>
<h2 class="h2">Where AI specifically helps professional services</h2>
<p class="body">Two highest-leverage AI applications at professional services firms:</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Content production at partner-quality scale.</strong> AI-assisted drafting of long-form thought leadership, speaking abstracts, industry briefs — produced from partner expertise via structured interviews, then partner-edited. Lets partners produce 3-4x output without 3-4x time investment.</li>
<li><strong>Referral nurture automation.</strong> AI agents follow up with referred prospects in the partner's voice (with partner approval), schedule intro meetings, and warm prospects up to a partner conversation. Solves the "I keep meaning to follow up with that referral" problem that loses meaningful new client work.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Full operating model: <a href="/ai-native-fractional-cmo" style="color:#00C853;">AI-native fractional CMO</a>.</p>
</div></section>


